JUnit runs the test and checks results; Mockito stands in for the things your class depends on.

## JUnit 5 essentials

```java
class CartTest {
  private Cart cart;

  @BeforeEach void setUp() { cart = new Cart(); }   // before every test

  @Test
  void emptyCartTotalsZero() {
    assertEquals(0, cart.total());
    assertTrue(cart.isEmpty());
    assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class, () -> cart.add(null));
  }

  @ParameterizedTest
  @ValueSource(ints = { 1, 5, 100 })
  void acceptsPositiveQuantities(int qty) { cart.add(item, qty); /* ... */ }
}
```

Common assertions: `assertEquals`, `assertTrue/False`, `assertNull/NotNull`, `assertThrows`,
`assertAll` (group several).

## Mockito — fake the collaborators

When your class depends on a service, **mock** it so the test stays about *your* class:

```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class CheckoutTest {
  @Mock PriceFormatter formatter;
  @Mock PaymentGateway gateway;
  @InjectMocks Checkout checkout;     // formatter + gateway injected in

  @Test
  void chargesFormattedTotal() {
    when(formatter.format(anyLong(), any())).thenReturn("19,99 €");  // stub
    when(gateway.charge(1999)).thenReturn(Result.OK);

    assertTrue(checkout.pay(1999, Locale.GERMANY));

    verify(gateway).charge(1999);     // behaviour check
  }
}
```

- **`when(...).thenReturn(...)`** — stub a return value.
- **`verify(...)`** — assert a method was (or wasn't, `never()`) called.
- **matchers** — `any()`, `eq()`, `anyLong()`; if you use one matcher, use them for all args.
- **`thenThrow(...)`** — simulate failure paths.

<Callout type="warn">Don't over-mock. Mock the **boundaries** (services, gateways, repositories) — not value objects or the class under test. A test full of mocks asserting mock interactions tests nothing real.</Callout>

For code that touches resources, `ValueMap`, or the resolver, **AEM Mocks** (`io.wcm`) gives you an
in-memory AEM — real Sling APIs, no server.

## Set up the context

```java
@ExtendWith(AemContextExtension.class)
class CardModelTest {
  private final AemContext ctx = new AemContext();   // in-memory resolver, bundle ctx, etc.
}
```

## Get content in

Either load a JSON snapshot of a content tree, or build resources programmatically:

```java
// from a test resource file
ctx.load().json("/com/example/card.json", "/content/card");

// or inline
ctx.build().resource("/content/card",
    "jcr:title", "Hello", "description", "World").commit();
```

## Adapt to your model

Register the model classes, set the current resource, and adapt:

```java
ctx.addModelsForClasses(Card.class);
ctx.currentResource("/content/card");

Card card = ctx.currentResource().adaptTo(Card.class);
assertEquals("Hello", card.getTitle());
```

## Mock the OSGi services a model needs

Register a real or mock service into the context so injection resolves:

```java
ctx.registerService(PriceFormatter.class, (cents, locale) -> "19,99 €");
// or register + activate your own component with config:
ctx.registerInjectActivateService(new ReportServiceImpl(),
    Map.of("endpoint", "https://test"));
```

## Requests, when the model is request-adaptable

```java
ctx.requestPathInfo().setSelectorString("teaser");
MockSlingHttpServletRequest req = ctx.request();
req.setResource(ctx.currentResource());
Teaser t = req.adaptTo(Teaser.class);
```

<Callout type="do">Use `AemContext` only when you actually need Sling APIs (resources, resolver, models). For pure logic, plain JUnit + Mockito is faster. Keep JSON fixtures small and named after the test.</Callout>

The Sling Context-Aware Configuration API defines configs as **annotated interfaces** — the same
OSGi-style metatype you already know, but resolved by content context.

## Define a configuration

```java
@Configuration(label = "Academy Site Config",
               description = "Per-site settings for the Academy")
public @interface SiteConfig {

  @Property(label = "Brand name")
  String brandName() default "Academy";

  @Property(label = "Newsletter enabled")
  boolean newsletterEnabled() default false;

  @Property(label = "Social links")
  String[] socialLinks();
}
```

Annotate with `@Configuration` (not OSGi's `@ObjectClassDefinition`) — that's what registers it with
CAC and surfaces it to editors.

## Read it for the current context

From a Sling Model, adapt the resource to a `ConfigurationBuilder` and ask for your config:

```java
@Model(adaptables = Resource.class)
public class FooterModel {

  @Self
  private Resource resource;

  private SiteConfig config;

  @PostConstruct
  void init() {
    config = resource.adaptTo(ConfigurationBuilder.class).as(SiteConfig.class);
  }

  public String getBrandName() { return config.brandName(); }
}
```

CAC resolves the value from the nearest `/conf` for that resource's context — no path logic in your
code.

## Singletons, lists & nested configs

- **Singleton** — `.as(SiteConfig.class)` (one set of values).
- **Collection** — `.asCollection(NavItem.class)` for a list of config items.
- **Nested** — a config property typed as another `@Configuration` interface for structured settings.

<Callout type="note">Context-aware **resources** work the same way: `adaptTo(ConfigurationResourceResolver.class)` returns the underlying `/conf` resources if you need raw nodes rather than a typed config.</Callout>

<Callout type="do">Type your config as an interface and read it via `ConfigurationBuilder` in `@PostConstruct`. Your model never knows *where* the value came from — CAC handles the context resolution and inheritance.</Callout>

CAC is testable with `AemContext` plus the **wcm.io Context-Aware Config** test support — you register
config values for a context and assert your model reads them.

## Set up

Use a context built with the CAC test plugin so `ConfigurationBuilder` resolves in-memory:

```java
@ExtendWith(AemContextExtension.class)
class FooterModelTest {
  private final AemContext ctx =
      new AemContextBuilder().plugin(CONTEXT_AWARE_CONFIG).build();
}
```

## Provide config for the context

Register the config class and write values for a content path, then point the current resource there:

```java
@Test
void readsBrandFromContext() {
  MockContextAwareConfig.registerAnnotationClasses(ctx, SiteConfig.class);
  ctx.create().resource("/content/academy",
      "sling:configRef", "/conf/academy");
  MockContextAwareConfig.writeConfiguration(ctx, "/content/academy",
      SiteConfig.class, "brandName", "Netcentric Academy");

  ctx.currentResource(ctx.create().resource("/content/academy/en"));
  ctx.addModelsForClasses(FooterModel.class);

  FooterModel model = ctx.currentResource().adaptTo(FooterModel.class);
  assertEquals("Netcentric Academy", model.getBrandName());
}
```

## What you're really testing

- The model **reads** the config (not the framework's resolution algorithm).
- **Inheritance/override**: write a value at a parent context and a different one at a child, and assert the nearest wins.
- **Defaults**: with no value written, your annotation `default` is returned.

<Callout type="do">Test that your model surfaces the **right value for the context** and falls back to defaults — write a parent and child config and assert the override. That's the behaviour authors rely on.</Callout>

Your extended model has one job: transform the delegate's output. So the test only needs to prove
*your override* behaves — the core model is already tested by Adobe.

## Test dependencies

In the `core` module's `pom.xml` you'll have JUnit 5, Mockito, and **AEM Mocks** (`io.wcm`):

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.wcm</groupId>
  <artifactId>io.wcm.testing.aem-mock.junit5</artifactId>
  <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

## Approach A — mock the delegate (fast, focused)

Since `getTitle()` just upper-cases `delegate.getTitle()`, mock the delegate and assert the transform:

```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class TeaserImplTest {
  @Test
  void uppercasesTitle() {
    Teaser delegate = mock(Teaser.class);
    when(delegate.getTitle()).thenReturn("Hello");

    TeaserImpl teaser = new TeaserImpl();
    // inject the private delegate (reflection helper or a test constructor)
    setField(teaser, "delegate", delegate);

    assertEquals("HELLO", teaser.getTitle());
  }
}
```

## Approach B — full adaptation with AemContext

For an end-to-end check, load content and adapt the request to your model:

```java
@ExtendWith(AemContextExtension.class)
class TeaserImplIT {
  private final AemContext ctx = new AemContext();

  @Test
  void rendersFromContent() {
    ctx.load().json("/teaser-content.json", "/content");
    ctx.addModelsForClasses(TeaserImpl.class);
    ctx.currentResource("/content/teaser");

    Teaser model = ctx.request().adaptTo(Teaser.class);
    assertEquals("HELLO", model.getTitle());
  }
}
```

<Callout type="do">Prefer **Approach A** for your override logic — it's a true unit test (no container, milliseconds). Use **Approach B** when you need to verify the delegation wiring itself resolves.</Callout>

<Callout type="note">Approach B needs the core component models on the test classpath to resolve the delegate. If that's heavy, mocking the delegate (A) keeps the test about *your* code, which is what unit tests are for. More on AEM Mocks in the **Unit Testing** module.</Callout>

Every element is a rectangular box. Getting layout right starts with understanding that box.

## The box model

From the inside out:

- **Content** — the text/image area
- **Padding** — space *inside* the border (transparent)
- **Border** — around the padding
- **Margin** — space *outside* the border (transparent)

![The CSS box model: a content box wrapped by padding, then border, then margin](img/css/box-model.svg)

```css
.box {
  width: 200px;     /* by default applies to the CONTENT box only */
  padding: 16px;
  border: 2px solid;
}
```

<Callout type="warn">By default `width`/`height` size only the **content** box, so padding + border are *added* on top — a 200px box with 16px padding is actually 234px wide.</Callout>

<Callout type="do">Set `box-sizing: border-box` (globally is fine) so `width` includes padding and border. It's what most projects do:</Callout>

```css
*, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }
```

Try it — flip `box-sizing` between `content-box` and `border-box`, or change the padding/border, and watch the box's total size change:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="box">200px wide?</div>`}
  css={`.box {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 6px solid #6b2fb3;
  box-sizing: content-box;   /* try: border-box */
  background: #f0ebf6;
}`}
/>

## `position`

| Value | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| `static` | default; normal flow; ignores `top/left/…` |
| `relative` | offset *from its own* position; original space is kept |
| `absolute` | removed from flow; positioned to nearest *positioned* ancestor |
| `fixed` | removed from flow; positioned to the viewport; stays on scroll |
| `sticky` | flows normally, then "sticks" within its container on scroll |

```css
.parent  { position: relative; }     /* establishes a containing block */
.badge   { position: absolute; top: 0; right: 0; }
```

<Callout type="note">`absolute` looks for the nearest ancestor with a `position` other than `static`. If there is none, it anchors to the document body.</Callout>

Try it — change `.badge`'s `position` (`absolute` / `relative` / `static`) and its `top` / `right` offsets, then flip the parent's `position` and watch where the badge anchors:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="parent">
  Card content
  <span class="badge">NEW</span>
</div>`}
  css={`.parent {
  position: relative;        /* the badge's containing block — try: static */
  height: 120px;
  padding: 1rem;
  background: #f0ebf6;
  border-radius: 8px;
}
.badge {
  position: absolute;        /* try: static / relative */
  top: 8px;
  right: 8px;                /* try: left: 8px / bottom: 8px */
  padding: .15rem .5rem;
  background: #6b2fb3;
  color: #fff;
  border-radius: 999px;
  font-size: .75rem;
}`}
/>

## z-index & stacking contexts

The whole idea in one line: **`z-index` is local.** It only ranks elements **inside the same
stacking context** — never across different ones.

A **stacking context** is a self-contained layer. A few things create one — most commonly a
**positioned** element with a `z-index`, but also `opacity < 1`, a `transform`, a `filter`, or
`will-change`.

The catch: once an element makes a context, its children are **sealed inside it**. Their `z-index`
only competes with each other — a child can't climb out, however big the number:

![Main (z-index 2) is painted over the whole Header (z-index 1) — including its Menu (z-index 9999) — because the Menu is trapped inside Header's stacking context](img/css/stacking-context.svg)

```css
.header       { position: relative; z-index: 1; }   /* a stacking context  */
.header .menu { position: absolute; z-index: 9999; } /* trapped inside it   */
.main         { position: relative; z-index: 2; }    /* a separate context  */
```

`.main` (2) beats `.header` (1), so it paints over the whole header — and the menu's `9999` never
gets compared against `.main` at all.

<Callout type="warn">"My `z-index: 9999` doesn't work!" almost always means it's trapped in a parent stacking context. Fix the **parent's** stacking, not the child's number.</Callout>

<Reveal title="For the curious: the exact paint order inside one context">

Within a single stacking context, the browser paints **back → front** in a fixed order:

![Painting order back to front: root, negative z-index, block-level boxes, floats, inline boxes, z-index 0 or auto, then positive z-index](img/css/stacking-order.svg)

</Reveal>

Custom properties (often called "CSS variables") hold a value you can reuse with `var()`. Unlike
Sass variables, they're **live in the browser** — they cascade, inherit, and can change at runtime.

<Callout type="note">📊 Companion slides: [CSS Custom Properties deck](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1yDIhkTrSCND1ISz2le_Y-MTawFsw49YN3D_fY3zMI54/edit?usp=sharing).</Callout>

## Declaring and using

```css
:root {
  --brand: #6b2fb3;
  --space: 1rem;
}

.button {
  background: var(--brand);
  padding: var(--space);
}
```

## Fallback values

```css
color: var(--accent, currentColor);   /* use currentColor if --accent is unset */
```

## They cascade and scope to elements

A custom property is scoped to the element it's declared on and inherits to descendants —
so you can **override per component or per state**:

```css
.card        { --pad: 1rem; padding: var(--pad); }
.card--roomy { --pad: 2rem; }            /* same rule, new value */
```

## Theming with one switch

Because they're live, flipping a value re-themes everything that uses it:

```css
:root        { --bg: #fff; --fg: #1c1c28; }
[data-theme="dark"] { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; }

body { background: var(--bg); color: var(--fg); }
```

<Callout type="note">This site's light/dark toggle is exactly this: it flips `data-theme` on `<html>`, and every `var(--…)` updates instantly — no extra CSS per component.</Callout>

Same component, re-themed by overriding the custom properties on a class — edit the values live:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="card">
  <h3>Card</h3>
  <button>Action</button>
</div>
<div class="card card--dark">
  <h3>Same card</h3>
  <button>Action</button>
</div>`}
  css={`.card {
  --brand: #6b2fb3;
  --bg: #f3f0f8;
  --fg: #1c1c28;
  background: var(--bg); color: var(--fg);
  padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: .5rem 0;
}
.card button { background: var(--brand); color: #fff; border: 0; padding: .4rem .8rem; border-radius: 6px; }
.card--dark { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; --brand: #b794ec; }`}
/>

<Callout type="do">Expose component "knobs" as custom properties (`--gap`, `--columns`). It makes components themeable and overridable without touching their internals.</Callout>

Responsive design delivers a layout that adapts to screen size, platform, and orientation. The core
tool is the **media query** — a block of CSS that only applies when the viewport (or device) matches
a condition.

## Anatomy of a media query

```css
.grid { display: block; }

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
}
```

A media query is a **media type** (`screen`, `print`, `all` — `screen` is implied) plus one or more
**feature conditions** in parentheses (`min-width`, `orientation`, …). When it matches, the rules
inside apply; otherwise they're ignored.

## Mobile-first (`min-width`)

Style the mobile layout first, then *add* changes upward with `min-width`:

```css
.nav { flex-direction: column; }          /* mobile default */

@media (min-width: 900px) {
  .nav { flex-direction: row; }            /* enhancement for wider screens */
}
```

- Mobile is the most-used platform.
- Mobile styles tend to be simpler, so they make a cleaner base.
- You only layer on complexity where there's room for it.

## `min-width` vs `max-width`

- **`min-width`** → mobile-first; you *enhance upward*. This is the recommended default.
- **`max-width`** → desktop-first; you *override downward*.

```css
/* desktop-first: base is the wide layout, then walk it back */
.sidebar { width: 320px; }
@media (max-width: 700px) {
  .sidebar { width: 100%; }
}
```

<Callout type="warn">Don't freely mix `min-` and `max-width` for the same component — overlapping ranges make it hard to reason about which rule wins. Pick one direction (usually mobile-first) and stay consistent.</Callout>

## Choosing breakpoints

Common starting points — but pick breakpoints where **your content** breaks, not for specific devices:

| Breakpoint | Typical target |
|---|---|
| `≥ 480px` | large phones |
| `≥ 768px` | tablets |
| `≥ 1024px` | small laptops |
| `≥ 1280px` | desktops |

<Callout type="do">Before reaching for a media query, see how far the layout gets with intrinsic sizing (Flexbox/Grid, `min()`/`max()`/`clamp()`, `flex-wrap`). The best breakpoint is often *no* breakpoint.</Callout>

## Combining conditions

```css
@media (min-width: 600px) and (max-width: 900px) { … }   /* both must match  */
@media (min-width: 600px), print { … }                   /* either (OR)      */
@media not all and (min-width: 600px) { … }              /* negate           */
```

## Modern range syntax

Newer, more readable comparison syntax (widely supported):

```css
@media (width >= 768px) { … }
@media (400px <= width <= 900px) { … }   /* an explicit range */
```

## Beyond width: other useful features

```css
@media (orientation: landscape) { … }
@media print { nav, .ads { display: none; } }   /* print stylesheet */
@media (min-resolution: 2dppx) { … }            /* retina / hi-dpi */
```

## Responding to user preferences

These accessibility-focused media features react to OS settings — use them, they're easy wins:

```css
/* respect users who asked for less motion */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * { animation: none !important; transition: none !important; }
}

/* honour the OS light/dark choice */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  :root { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; }
}
```

<Callout type="note">`prefers-reduced-motion` and `prefers-color-scheme` cost almost nothing to add and make a real difference — reduced-motion prevents nausea/vestibular issues, and respecting dark mode is increasingly expected.</Callout>

## Try it — cross a breakpoint live

**Drag the preview's right edge** to resize the viewport and watch the grid switch from one column
to two as it crosses `min-width: 420px` — a real media query, no JavaScript:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="grid">
  <div class="box">1</div>
  <div class="box">2</div>
  <div class="box">3</div>
  <div class="box">4</div>
</div>`}
  css={`.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;     /* mobile default: one column */
  gap: 1rem;
}
.box {
  padding: 1.5rem;
  background: #6b2fb3;
  color: #fff;
  border-radius: 8px;
  font-weight: 700;
  text-align: center;
}
@media (min-width: 420px) {
  .grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }   /* two columns when wide enough */
}`}
/>

Two modern layout systems. Rule of thumb: **Flexbox for one dimension** (a row or a column),
**Grid for two dimensions** (rows *and* columns).

## Flexbox

A flex container distributes space among its items along a **main axis**, with alignment on the
**cross axis**.

```css
.toolbar {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;        /* main axis = horizontal */
  justify-content: space-between;  /* along main axis   */
  align-items: center;             /* along cross axis  */
  gap: 1rem;
}
.toolbar .spacer { flex: 1; }       /* grow to fill      */
```

**Terminology:** flex container · flex items · flex-direction · main axis · cross axis.

### Play with every flex property

Toggle each property below and watch the boxes rearrange. The generated CSS updates live, so you
can connect each value to its effect — try `flex-direction: column` with different `align-items`, or
add `items` until `flex-wrap: wrap` kicks in.

<LayoutLab mode="flex" />

<Callout type="note">`align-items` aligns on the **cross axis** — so with `flex-direction: row` it moves items up/down, but with `column` it moves them left/right. Watch the boxes flip behaviour when you change direction. (`baseline` lines up the items' text baselines — that's why the boxes have different text sizes.)</Callout>

### A real-world example

Now the same properties on something concrete — change `justify-content`, `gap`, or `flex-direction`:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="toolbar">
  <span>Logo</span>
  <span class="spacer"></span>
  <button>Login</button>
</div>`}
  css={`.toolbar {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 1rem;
  padding: .75rem 1rem;
  background: #f0ebf6;
  border-radius: 8px;
}
.spacer { flex: 1; }            /* pushes the button to the right */
button {
  border: 0;
  padding: .5rem 1rem;
  border-radius: 6px;
  background: #6b2fb3;
  color: #fff;
}`}
/>

## CSS Grid

<Callout type="note">📊 Companion slides: [CSS Grid deck](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1OxpNvraVgeYg1-zO1bqyOAP5UgZwoy0Y98H-4uAQh8E/edit?usp=sharing).</Callout>

Grid lays out items into a 2-D grid of **tracks** (rows/columns) and **areas**.

```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;   /* sidebar + fluid content */
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
```

**Terminology:** grid container · grid items · grid line · grid cell · grid track · grid area.

### Play with grid layout

Pick a preset for `grid-template-columns` / `grid-template-rows` — or **type your own** value in the
field — and watch the boxes flow into the tracks. `justify-items`/`align-items` position each item
*inside* its cell; `justify-content`/`align-content` position the whole grid *within* the container;
`grid-auto-flow` controls the direction items are placed.

<LayoutLab mode="grid" />

<Callout type="note">Two things worth noticing as you experiment: `repeat(auto-fit, minmax(60px, 1fr))` reflows the column count on its own (no media query — the pattern behind the card grid below). And `justify-content`/`align-content` only have a visible effect when the tracks **don't fill** the container — try fixed columns like `repeat(3, 80px)` to see them move the whole grid.</Callout>

## New units, functions & keywords

| | Examples |
|---|---|
| **Units** | `fr` (fraction of free space) |
| **Functions** | `minmax(200px, 1fr)`, `repeat(3, 1fr)`, `fit-content(300px)` |
| **Sizing keywords** | `min-content`, `max-content` |

```css
.cards {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
}
```

<Callout type="do">`repeat(auto-fit, minmax(…, 1fr))` gives you a responsive card grid with **no media queries** — it fits as many columns as will hold the minimum width, then stretches them.</Callout>

<Callout type="note">Use `gap` for spacing instead of margins on items — it works in both Flexbox and Grid and never adds an edge gap.</Callout>

Let the browser interpolate the in-between states when something changes — no JS needed.

## Transitions

A transition animates a property *when its value changes* (e.g. on `:hover`).

```css
.button {
  background: var(--brand);
  transition: background 200ms ease, transform 200ms ease;
}
.button:hover {
  background: var(--accent);
  transform: translateY(-2px);
}
```

The longhands: `transition-property`, `transition-duration`, `transition-delay`,
`transition-timing-function` — or the `transition` shorthand.

## Animations

For multi-step or looping motion, define `@keyframes` and attach with `animation`.

```css
@keyframes fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(8px); }
  to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
}

.card {
  animation: fade-in 400ms ease both;
}
```

Animation longhands you'll use: `animation-name`, `animation-duration`, `animation-delay`,
`animation-iteration-count`, `animation-direction`, `animation-timing-function`,
`animation-fill-mode` — or the `animation` shorthand.

## Performance

<Callout type="warn">Not every property is animatable, and some are **expensive**. Animating `width`, `height`, `top`, or `left` triggers layout on every frame.</Callout>

<Callout type="do">Prefer animating `transform` and `opacity` — the browser can composite them on the GPU without re-laying-out the page. And respect `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` for accessibility.</Callout>

```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  *, *::before, *::after { animation: none !important; transition: none !important; }
}
```

Hover the button (transition) and watch the badge (keyframe animation) — tweak the timings:

