Two modern tools for *controlling the cascade itself* — so specificity wars and source order
stop deciding your styles for you.

## Cascade layers — `@layer`

`@layer` lets you define explicit, ordered buckets. **Layer order beats specificity**: a rule in
a later layer wins over a rule in an earlier layer, *even if the earlier one is more specific*.

```css
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;   /* declare order once */

@layer base {
  a { color: blue; }
}
@layer components {
  .link { color: rebeccapurple; }   /* wins over base, regardless of specificity */
}
```

<Callout type="do">Put third-party/reset CSS in an early layer and your own styles in a later one. You can then override a library with a *simple* class instead of escalating specificity or using `!important`.</Callout>

- Unlayered styles count as the **highest** layer (they win over layered styles).
- `@layer name { }` adds to a layer; re-using the name appends to it.

## Scoped styles — `@scope`

`@scope` limits where rules apply, with a root and an optional lower boundary — useful for
component styling without leaking out.

```css
@scope (.card) to (.card__content) {
  /* applies inside .card, but NOT past a .card__content boundary */
  img { border-radius: 8px; }
  a   { color: var(--brand); }
}
```

- The first parenthesis is the **scope root**; the `to (…)` is the **scope limit** (a "donut").
- Proximity matters: in `@scope`, the closest-scoped rule wins on ties.

See layer order beat specificity — the later layer wins even though the other selector is more
specific. Reorder the `@layer` line and watch the colour flip:

<Playground
  html={`<p class="note">Layer order beats specificity.</p>`}
  css={`@layer base, theme;

@layer theme {
  p { color: rebeccapurple; }   /* later layer */
}
@layer base {
  .note { color: gray; }        /* earlier layer, MORE specific — yet loses */
}`}
/>

<Callout type="note">Layers and scope reduce the need for deeply-nested selectors and `!important`. With BEM keeping specificity flat and layers keeping order explicit, the cascade becomes something you *design* rather than fight.</Callout>

The Java Collections Framework is everyday AEM code — Sling Models return lists, services cache maps.
Two contracts trip people up: **hashing** (for `HashSet`/`HashMap`) and **ordering** (`Comparable`).

## The big three

| Type | Keeps | Order | Backed by |
|---|---|---|---|
| `List` | duplicates, by index | insertion | `ArrayList` (random access), `LinkedList` |
| `Set` | unique elements | none (`HashSet`) / sorted (`TreeSet`) | hash table / tree |
| `Map` | key → value | none (`HashMap`) / sorted (`TreeMap`) | hash table / tree |

## Hashing: the `equals()` + `hashCode()` contract

`HashSet` and `HashMap` find elements by **`hashCode()`** (which bucket) then confirm with
**`equals()`**. So they must be overridden **together** and stay consistent:

- Equal objects (`a.equals(b)`) **must** return the same `hashCode()`.
- Unequal objects *may* share a hashCode (a collision) — that's fine, just slower.

```java
public final class Sku {
  private final String code;
  public Sku(String code) { this.code = code; }

  @Override public boolean equals(Object o) {
    if (this == o) return true;
    if (!(o instanceof Sku)) return false;
    return code.equals(((Sku) o).code);
  }
  @Override public int hashCode() { return Objects.hash(code); }
}
```

<Callout type="warn">Override `equals()` but **not** `hashCode()` and your objects vanish in a `HashMap` — two "equal" keys land in different buckets. Always override both, over the same fields.</Callout>

## Ordering: `Comparable` vs `Comparator`

For **sorted** structures (`TreeSet`, `TreeMap`, `Collections.sort`) you need ordering, not hashing:

- **`Comparable`** — the type's *natural order*, one per class: `int compareTo(T other)`.
- **`Comparator`** — an *external* order, as many as you like; ideal for multiple sort keys.

```java
// natural order on the class
class Lesson implements Comparable<Lesson> {
  int order;
  public int compareTo(Lesson o) { return Integer.compare(this.order, o.order); }
}

// ad-hoc orders, composable
list.sort(Comparator.comparing(Lesson::getTitle).thenComparingInt(l -> l.order));
```

<Callout type="do">**Hash or Comparable?** Need fast lookup with no order → `HashMap`/`HashSet` (define `equals`/`hashCode`). Need sorted iteration → `TreeMap`/`TreeSet` (define `Comparable`/`Comparator`).</Callout>

<Reveal title="Gotcha: keep `compareTo` consistent with `equals`">

For `TreeSet`/`TreeMap`, ordering *is* equality — two elements are "the same" when `compareTo` returns
`0`, **regardless of `equals`**. If your `compareTo` only looks at one field, a `TreeSet` will treat
two objects that differ elsewhere as duplicates and silently drop one. Keep `compareTo` consistent
with `equals` unless you mean otherwise.

</Reveal>

Every Netcentric component is a **class**, so this is the one concept to get really comfortable with.
We'll build it up slowly — what a class is, what `this` means, and why you'll sometimes need `bind`.

## Why a class?

A **class** is a *blueprint* for making objects. You describe the shape and behaviour once, then stamp
out as many **instances** as you need — each with its own data. Think of one `Dropdown` class and ten
dropdowns on a page: same code, ten independent instances.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  C["class Greeter<br/>(the blueprint)"] -->|"new Greeter('Ada')"| A["instance a<br/>this.name = 'Ada'"]
  C -->|"new Greeter('Linus')"| B["instance b<br/>this.name = 'Linus'"]
```

## Step 1 — your first class

```js
class Greeter {
  // The constructor runs ONCE, the moment you create an instance with `new`.
  // Its job: set up the instance's starting data (its "state").
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;          // store `name` ON this instance
  }

  // A method — a function that belongs to the class.
  greet() {
    console.log(`Hello ${this.name}`);
  }
}
```

Three words to be clear on:

- **`new`** — builds a fresh, empty object and runs the `constructor`.
- **property** — a piece of data on the instance (`this.name`).
- **method** — a function the instance can run (`greet`).

## Step 2 — create and use an instance

```js
const g = new Greeter('World'); // `new` builds the instance + runs the constructor
g.greet();                      // Hello World
```

`new Greeter('World')` does three things: makes a new empty object, runs `constructor('World')` with
`this` pointing at that new object, and hands it back to you.

## Step 3 — instances are independent

Make two and each keeps its **own** `name`. The methods are shared; the data is not:

```js
const a = new Greeter('Ada');
const b = new Greeter('Linus');

a.greet(); // Hello Ada
b.greet(); // Hello Linus
```

<Callout type="note">That independence is the whole point: the component loader does `new Dropdown(el)` once **per element**, so each dropdown keeps its own state and never interferes with the others.</Callout>

## Step 4 — what `this` actually is

Inside a method, **`this` is whatever is to the left of the dot when the method is called.**

```js
class Greeter {
  constructor(name) { this.name = name; }
  greet() {
    console.log(`Hello ${this.name}`);   // `this` = the object that called greet()
  }
}

const a = new Greeter('Ada');
const b = new Greeter('Linus');

a.greet();   // left of the dot is `a` → this === a → "Hello Ada"
b.greet();   // left of the dot is `b` → this === b → "Hello Linus"
```

Same method, two different results — because `this` is decided by **who's left of the dot at call
time**, not when you wrote the class. That one sentence explains the gotcha below.

## Step 5 — the classic gotcha: losing `this`

When you pass a method somewhere as a **callback**, you detach it from its object. Now there's nothing
"to the left of the dot", so `this` is no longer the instance (it's `undefined` in strict mode):

```js
const g = new Greeter('Ada');

button.addEventListener('click', g.greet);   // ❌ `this` is lost → error / "Hello undefined"
```

`addEventListener` later calls the function on its own, like `greet()` — with no `g.` in front — so
inside `greet`, `this.name` blows up.

## Step 6 — three ways to keep `this`

```js
// 1) Arrow wrapper — call it the normal way (with `g.` in front), so `this` stays `g`
button.addEventListener('click', () => g.greet());

// 2) .bind(g) — lock `this` to g permanently (more on this next)
button.addEventListener('click', g.greet.bind(g));

// 3) Class field arrow method — auto-binds `this` to the instance (modern, common in components)
class Greeter {
  greet = () => { console.log(`Hello ${this.name}`); };
}
```

<Callout type="warn">Passing `obj.method` directly as a callback detaches it from `obj`. Wrap it in an arrow (`() => obj.method()`), use **`.bind(obj)`**, or define the method as a **class-field arrow** — otherwise `this` won't point at your instance.</Callout>

## `bind` — what it does and when to reach for it

`obj.method.bind(obj)` doesn't call the method. It returns a **brand-new function** whose `this` is
**permanently** locked to `obj`, no matter how it's later called.

```js
const greetAda = g.greet.bind(g);
greetAda();        // Hello Ada — `this` is locked to g forever
```

### The everyday use — event handlers in a component

The main reason you'll reach for `bind`: handlers run on `this.element`, but the browser calls them
detached. Bind in the constructor so `this` still means the instance:

```js
class Dropdown {
  constructor(element) {
    this.element = element;
    this.open = false;
    // lock `this` so handleClick can use this.element / this.open
    this.element.addEventListener('click', this.handleClick.bind(this));
  }

  handleClick() {
    this.open = !this.open;            // `this` is the Dropdown instance ✅
    this.element.classList.toggle('is-open', this.open);
  }
}
```

<Callout type="do">In components, prefer a **class-field arrow** (`handleClick = () => {…}`) or **bind in the constructor** — both keep `this` pointing at the instance when the browser calls the handler.</Callout>

## Try it — watch `this` get lost, then fixed

