Three pieces: a **producer** adds the job, a **consumer** processes it, and optional **queue config**
tunes how it runs.

## Produce a job

Inject `JobManager` and add a job to a topic with a property map:

```java
@Reference
private JobManager jobManager;

public void enqueueEmail(String to, String template) {
  Map<String, Object> props = Map.of("to", to, "template", template);
  jobManager.addJob("academy/job/email", props);   // returns immediately
}
```

## Consume a job

Register a `JobConsumer` for that topic; return a **`JobResult`**:

```java
@Component(service = JobConsumer.class,
           property = JobConsumer.PROPERTY_TOPICS + "=academy/job/email")
public class EmailJobConsumer implements JobConsumer {

  @Override
  public JobResult process(Job job) {
    String to = job.getProperty("to", String.class);
    try {
      sendEmail(to, job.getProperty("template", String.class));
      return JobResult.OK;          // done — remove from queue
    } catch (TransientException e) {
      return JobResult.FAILED;      // retry later (counts toward max retries)
    } catch (Exception e) {
      return JobResult.CANCEL;      // give up — don't retry
    }
  }
}
```

- **`OK`** — success, job removed.
- **`FAILED`** — retry (up to the queue's max retries, with delay).
- **`CANCEL`** — permanent failure, no retry.

## Immediate vs scheduled

- **Immediate** — `addJob(topic, props)` runs as soon as a consumer is free.
- **Scheduled** — use the `JobBuilder` to run later or on a cron, returning a `ScheduledJobInfo`:

```java
jobManager.createJob("academy/job/digest").properties(props)
    .schedule().daily(2, 0).add();      // every day at 02:00
```

## Queue configuration

Tune a topic's processing with an `org.apache.sling.event.jobs.QueueConfiguration` OSGi config:

- **type** — `ORDERED` (one at a time, in order) vs `TOPIC_ROUND_ROBIN`/`UNORDERED` (parallel).
- **maxParallel** — how many run concurrently.
- **retries** & **retryDelay** — failure handling.
- **topics** — which topic(s) this queue serves.

<Callout type="do">Return `FAILED` only for **transient** errors (retry makes sense) and `CANCEL` for permanent ones — otherwise you fill the queue with doomed retries. Use an **ORDERED** queue when sequence matters, parallel when it doesn't.</Callout>

A model is mostly **injection annotations** — each one pulls a different thing into a field. Prefer the
*specific* annotation over the generic `@Inject`; it's clearer and faster.

## The annotations you'll actually use

| Annotation | Injects |
|---|---|
| `@ValueMapValue` | a property from the resource's `ValueMap` |
| `@ChildResource` | a child resource (adapt it to another model) |
| `@ScriptVariable` | HTL bindings — `currentPage`, `resource`, `pageManager` |
| `@OSGiService` | an OSGi service by its interface |
| `@Self` | the adaptable itself (the resource/request) |
| `@SlingObject` | `ResourceResolver`, `SlingHttpServletRequest`, etc. |

```java
@Model(adaptables = Resource.class, defaultInjectionStrategy = DefaultInjectionStrategy.OPTIONAL)
public class Teaser {
  @ValueMapValue @Default(values = "Untitled")
  private String title;

  @ValueMapValue(name = "fileReference")
  private String image;

  @ChildResource
  private Resource cta;            // /teaser/cta

  @OSGiService
  private PriceFormatter formatter;

  @ScriptVariable
  private Page currentPage;
}
```

## Required vs optional, and defaults

- With `OPTIONAL` default strategy, an unfilled field is just `null`.
- Mark a field **`@Required`** when adaptation should fail without it.
- Use **`@Default(values = ...)`** to supply a fallback instead of `null`.
- Rename with `@ValueMapValue(name = "fileReference")` when the JCR property name differs from the field.

## Initialise derived state with `@PostConstruct`

Injection happens first; then a `@PostConstruct` method runs to compute derived fields:

```java
@PostConstruct
protected void init() {
  this.hasImage = StringUtils.isNotBlank(image);
}
```

<Callout type="warn">Don't do heavy work in getters (they may be called repeatedly from HTL). Compute once in `@PostConstruct` and store the result.</Callout>

<Callout type="do">Reach for the **specific** annotation (`@ValueMapValue`, `@ChildResource`, `@OSGiService`) rather than `@Inject`. It documents intent and avoids ambiguous resolution.</Callout>

Two design decisions every model faces: **what do you adapt from**, and **how is the dependency
wired in**.

## Adaptable: `Resource` vs `SlingHttpServletRequest`

```java
@Model(adaptables = { Resource.class, SlingHttpServletRequest.class })
```

- **`Resource`** — context-free. The model only knows the content node. Adaptable from JSON exporters,
  Groovy, tests, and other models. **Default to this.**
- **`SlingHttpServletRequest`** — request-scoped. You can inject `@RequestAttribute`, request
  parameters, the current style/`Designer`, the resolved page via request context, and read selectors.
  Use it **only when you genuinely need request data**.

Listing both makes the model adaptable either way; request-only injections simply stay null when
adapted from a resource.

<Callout type="warn">A request-adaptable model can't be exported by the Sling Model Exporter from a plain resource, and is harder to unit-test. Don't reach for `SlingHttpServletRequest` just out of habit — most components only need the `Resource`.</Callout>

## Injection style: field + `@PostConstruct` vs constructor

**Field injection** (the common style) — Sling Models sets the fields, then calls `@PostConstruct`:

```java
@Model(adaptables = Resource.class)
public class Card {
  @ValueMapValue private String title;
  @OSGiService  private PriceFormatter formatter;

  @PostConstruct protected void init() { /* derive state */ }
}
```

**Constructor injection** — dependencies arrive as constructor parameters, so fields can be `final`
and the object is fully initialised on creation (great for immutability and testing):

```java
@Model(adaptables = Resource.class)
public class Card {
  private final String title;

  @Inject
  public Card(@ValueMapValue String title) {
    this.title = title;
  }
}
```

<Callout type="do">**Constructor injection** gives you `final` fields and a valid-by-construction object — nice for testability. **Field + `@PostConstruct`** is more concise and the AEM norm. Pick one style per project and be consistent.</Callout>

<Callout type="note">"Constructor vs activation": with constructor injection the object is ready the moment it's built; with field injection there's a two-phase lifecycle (inject → `@PostConstruct`). Don't read injected fields in a field-injection **constructor** — they aren't set yet; use `@PostConstruct`.</Callout>

When logic doesn't belong to one component — formatting prices, calling an API, shared business rules —
it becomes an **OSGi service**: a singleton the container manages and injects where needed.

## Interface + implementation

Define the **contract** as an interface and the **implementation** as an `@Component` that provides it:

```java
public interface PriceFormatter {
  String format(long cents, Locale locale);
}

@Component(service = PriceFormatter.class)
public class PriceFormatterImpl implements PriceFormatter {
  public String format(long cents, Locale locale) {
    return NumberFormat.getCurrencyInstance(locale).format(cents / 100.0);
  }
}
```

Consumers depend on the **interface**, never the impl — so you can swap or mock it.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  I["PriceFormatter<br/>(interface = contract)"] -.implements.- Impl["PriceFormatterImpl<br/>@Component"]
  Impl -->|"registered"| Reg[("OSGi Service Registry")]
  Reg -->|"@Reference / @OSGiService"| C["Consumer<br/>(service or model)"]
```

## Consuming a service with `@Reference`

```java
@Component(service = ReportService.class)
public class ReportServiceImpl implements ReportService {
  @Reference
  private PriceFormatter formatter;        // injected by the container
}
```

In a Sling Model you use `@OSGiService` instead — same idea, model-side.

## Cardinality & optionality

A `@Reference` says how many providers it needs and whether it's mandatory:

- **Mandatory** (default) — the component won't activate until the reference is satisfied.
- **Optional** — `cardinality = OPTIONAL`; the component runs without it (field may be null).
- **Multiple** — `cardinality = MULTIPLE`; inject a `List<T>` of all providers (e.g. a set of pluggable handlers).

```java
@Reference(cardinality = ReferenceCardinality.MULTIPLE,
           policy = ReferencePolicy.DYNAMIC)
private volatile List<AssetHandler> handlers;
```

## Immediate components

```java
@Component(immediate = true)
```

By default a service component is **lazy** — instantiated when first used. `immediate = true` activates
it at bundle start (use it for listeners/schedulers that must run without being referenced).

<Callout type="do">Program to the **interface**. Keep services single-purpose. Use **mandatory** references for true dependencies and **optional/multiple** for pluggable extensions — and check the component's state in `/system/console/components` if it won't activate (usually an unsatisfied reference).</Callout>

Services shouldn't hard-code endpoints or feature flags. **OSGi configuration** externalises those
values — editable in the console and deployable per environment.

## Define the config: `@ObjectClassDefinition` + `@Designate`

```java
@ObjectClassDefinition(name = "Academy — Report Service")
public @interface ReportConfig {
  @AttributeDefinition(name = "API endpoint")
  String endpoint() default "https://api.example.com";

  @AttributeDefinition(name = "Enabled")
  boolean enabled() default true;

  @AttributeDefinition(name = "Timeout (ms)")
  int timeout() default 5000;
}
```

Bind it to the component with **`@Designate`** and read it in **`@Activate`**:

```java
@Component(service = ReportService.class)
@Designate(ocd = ReportConfig.class)
public class ReportServiceImpl implements ReportService {
  private String endpoint;

  @Activate @Modified
  protected void activate(ReportConfig config) {
    this.endpoint = config.endpoint();
  }
}
```

`@Activate` runs on start (and `@Modified` on config change) — so updating the config re-applies
without a restart.

## Deploy config as `.cfg.json`

A console edit isn't version-controlled. Ship the config in the repo as a **`.cfg.json`** whose
filename is the component's PID:

```text
ui.apps/.../apps/academy/osgiconfig/config/
    com.example.core.services.ReportServiceImpl.cfg.json
```

```json
{ "endpoint": "https://api.example.com", "enabled": true, "timeout": 5000 }
```

## Per-environment with run modes

Put the file in a **run-mode** folder and AEM applies only the matching one:

```text
config/                 ← always
config.author/          ← author only
config.publish.prod/    ← only when publish AND prod are active
```

<Callout type="do">Keep secrets and environment URLs in **run-mode config folders**, not code. The same artifact then carries the right values for dev / stage / prod. (This is the OSGi/run-mode topic from Advanced AEM, applied to your own service.)</Callout>

<Callout type="warn">The `.cfg.json` filename **must** equal the component PID (usually the impl FQCN). A typo means the file is ignored and your defaults silently win.</Callout>

**Jest** is the de-facto test runner for JavaScript front ends. It finds your test files, runs them,
and reports results — batteries included (assertions, mocking, coverage, a DOM environment).

## Anatomy of a test

```js
import { sum } from './math.js';

describe('sum()', () => {
  test('adds two positive numbers', () => {
    expect(sum(2, 3)).toBe(5);
  });

  it('handles negative numbers', () => {   // it() is an alias for test()
    expect(sum(-2, 3)).toBe(1);
  });
});
```

- **`describe(name, fn)`** — groups related tests into a suite (you can nest them).
- **`test(name, fn)`** / **`it(name, fn)`** — a single test case. `it` reads nicely:
  *"it handles negative numbers"*.
- **`expect(value)`** — wraps a value so you can assert on it with a **matcher** (next lesson).

## Running tests

```bash
npx jest                 # run all tests once
npx jest --watch         # re-run on change (only related to git changes)
npx jest math.test.js    # run one file
npx jest -t "negative"   # run tests whose name matches
```

A typical `package.json`:

```json
{
  "scripts": { "test": "jest", "test:watch": "jest --watch" }
}
```

## The lifecycle hooks

Run setup/teardown around tests so each one starts clean:

```js
beforeAll(() => { /* once, before all tests in this file/suite */ });
beforeEach(() => { /* before every test — reset state here */ });
afterEach(() => { /* after every test — clean up */ });
afterAll(() => { /* once, after all tests */ });
```

<Callout type="do">Put shared setup in `beforeEach` so every test is **independent** — tests must pass in any order and never rely on state left by another test.</Callout>

To test a unit in **isolation**, you replace its dependencies (other modules, network, timers) with
**mocks** — fake versions you control and can inspect.

## Mock functions — `jest.fn()`

```js
const onClick = jest.fn();

button.addEventListener('click', onClick);
button.click();

expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.any(Event));
```

Control what a mock returns:

```js
const getUser = jest.fn()
  .mockReturnValue({ name: 'Ada' });        // sync
const fetchUser = jest.fn()
  .mockResolvedValue({ name: 'Ada' });       // resolves a promise
const failing = jest.fn()
  .mockRejectedValue(new Error('boom'));     // rejects
```

## Mocking modules — `jest.mock`

Replace an entire imported module:

```js
import { sendEvent } from './analytics.js';
jest.mock('./analytics.js');   // auto-mock: every export becomes a jest.fn()

test('tracks a click', () => {
  handleClick();
  expect(sendEvent).toHaveBeenCalledWith('cta_click');
});
```

Or provide a custom factory:

```js
jest.mock('./config.js', () => ({ API_BASE: 'https://test.local' }));
```

## Mocking an API (fetch)

```js
beforeEach(() => {
  global.fetch = jest.fn().mockResolvedValue({
    ok: true,
    json: async () => ({ id: 1, name: 'Ada' })
  });
});
afterEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks());

test('loads the user', async () => {
  const user = await loadUser(1);
  expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/users/1');
  expect(user.name).toBe('Ada');
});
```

<Callout type="do">Reset mocks between tests — `jest.clearAllMocks()` (clears calls) or `jest.resetAllMocks()` (clears calls *and* implementations) in `afterEach` — so call counts don't leak across tests.</Callout>

<Callout type="warn">Mock at the **boundary** (network, timers, third-party modules), not your own logic. If you mock the very thing you're testing, the test proves nothing. Over-mocking also makes tests brittle and detached from reality.</Callout>

Front-end code is full of async work — fetches, timeouts, animations. The golden rule: **the test
must wait** for the async work, or it passes before the assertion even runs.

## async / await (preferred)

```js
test('loads the user', async () => {
  const user = await loadUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('Ada');
});
```

<Callout type="warn">Forgetting to `await` is the #1 async-test bug: the test finishes and **passes before** the assertion runs. If a test "can't fail", check that you awaited the async call.</Callout>

## `.resolves` / `.rejects`

Assert on a promise's outcome directly:

```js
await expect(loadUser(1)).resolves.toMatchObject({ name: 'Ada' });
await expect(loadUser(0)).rejects.toThrow('not found');
```

## Fake timers

Don't make tests wait real seconds for `setTimeout`/`setInterval` — **fake the clock** and advance it:

```js
test('debounce fires once after 300ms', () => {
  jest.useFakeTimers();
  const fn = jest.fn();
  const debounced = debounce(fn, 300);

  debounced(); debounced(); debounced();
  expect(fn).not.toHaveBeenCalled();

  jest.advanceTimersByTime(300);   // fast-forward
  expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);

  jest.useRealTimers();
});
```

Useful timer controls: `jest.advanceTimersByTime(ms)`, `jest.runAllTimers()`,
`jest.runOnlyPendingTimers()`.

<Callout type="do">Use fake timers for anything time-based (debounce, throttle, polling, auto-dismiss). Tests stay **fast and deterministic** instead of sleeping for real.</Callout>

Front-end units often touch the **DOM**. Jest runs them in **jsdom** — a JavaScript implementation
of the browser DOM — so you can create elements, dispatch events, and assert on the result without a
real browser.

## The jsdom environment

```js
/**
 * @jest-environment jsdom
 */
```

Add that comment at the top of a DOM test file, or set it globally in `jest.config.js`:

```js
export default { testEnvironment: 'jsdom' };
```

In jsdom you get `document`, `window`, events, `querySelector`, etc.

## Render markup, then assert

```js
test('renders the label', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `
    <button class="cta">Subscribe</button>
  `;
  const button = document.querySelector('.cta');
  expect(button).toHaveTextContent('Subscribe');   // jest-dom matcher
});
```

## Testing events

```js
test('toggles open state on click', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `<button class="menu" aria-expanded="false">Menu</button>`;
  const button = document.querySelector('.menu');

  button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const open = button.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
    button.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!open));
  });

  button.click();
  expect(button).toHaveAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
});
```

## Testing a component (the loader pattern)

The JavaScript track's components take an `element` + `options`. That makes them easy to unit-test —
render markup, instantiate the class, assert on the DOM:

```js
import MyComponent from './my-component.js';

test('writes the param text into the element', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `<div><span class="my-component__text"></span></div>`;
  const el = document.querySelector('div');

  new MyComponent(el, { text: 'Hello' });

  expect(el.querySelector('.my-component__text')).toHaveTextContent('Hello');
});
```

<Callout type="do">Test what the **user experiences** — visible text, attributes, and behaviour after an interaction — not internal structure. That keeps tests stable when you refactor the markup.</Callout>

<Callout type="warn">jsdom is **not a real browser**: no real layout, no painting, limited support for some APIs (e.g. `getBoundingClientRect` returns zeros). For true rendering/visual behaviour, use an E2E tool (Playwright/Cypress) — that's the top of the pyramid, not unit testing.</Callout>

Tests are code you'll read far more than you write. Keep them **discoverable, consistent, and
readable**.

## Where tests live & how they're named

Two common conventions (Jest finds both by default):

```text
# 1) next to the source (co-located)
src/utils/format.js
src/utils/format.test.js

# 2) in a __tests__ folder
src/utils/__tests__/format.test.js
```

- Use `.test.js` (or `.spec.js`) so Jest picks them up.
- **Co-locating** tests next to the source keeps them visible and easy to update together.

## Structure a suite to mirror the code

Use `describe` per unit, and nested `describe`s per scenario:

```js
describe('formatPrice()', () => {
  describe('with a valid amount', () => {
    it('formats with two decimals', () => { /* … */ });
    it('adds the currency symbol', () => { /* … */ });
  });

  describe('with invalid input', () => {
    it('throws on a negative amount', () => { /* … */ });
  });
});
```

## Write test names as sentences

The name should describe **behaviour**, so a failure reads like a spec:

<Callout type="dont">`test('test1')` · `test('formatPrice works')` — tells you nothing when it fails.</Callout>
<Callout type="do">`it('adds the currency symbol after the amount')` — reads as "formatPrice → with a valid amount → it adds the currency symbol after the amount".</Callout>

## Keep tests DRY — but readable

Factor repeated setup into `beforeEach` or small helpers/factories, but keep each test's **intent**
obvious at a glance:

```js
function makeUser(overrides = {}) {
  return { id: 1, name: 'Ada', active: true, ...overrides };
}

test('inactive users are hidden', () => {
  expect(isVisible(makeUser({ active: false }))).toBe(false);
});
```

<Callout type="warn">Don't over-abstract. A test with so much shared setup that you can't tell what it does is worse than a little duplication. Optimise for **readability over DRY** in tests.</Callout>

This is the **mid-module checkpoint** — apply lessons **01–05** by setting up Jest and testing pure
logic, mocks, and async code. **Keep your project**: the [final assignment](assignment) adds DOM
tests, organization, and coverage on top.

<Callout type="note">Test **behaviour**, not implementation. A good suite goes red when you introduce a real bug and survives a refactor that keeps behaviour the same.</Callout>

## Setup

- [ ] Install and configure Jest (`jest`, `@testing-library/jest-dom`, `jest-environment-jsdom`)
- [ ] Add `"test": "jest"` and a `"test:watch"` script
- [ ] Confirm `npx jest` runs and finds `*.test.js` files

## Part A — Pure logic & matchers (Beginner)

Given `formatPrice(cents)`, `slugify(text)`, and `clamp(n, min, max)`:

- [ ] Test happy paths with the **right matchers** (`toBe`, `toEqual`, `toThrow`)
- [ ] Cover **edge cases**: `0`, empty string, negative, boundary values
- [ ] Name tests as behaviour sentences; group with `describe`

**Acceptance:** each function has happy-path + edge-case tests; matchers are specific (e.g. `toHaveLength`, `toThrow('…')`).

## Part B — Mocking & async (Intermediate)

Given `loadUser(id)` that calls `fetch`, and a `debounce(fn, ms)` helper:

- [ ] **Mock `fetch`** (`jest.fn().mockResolvedValue(...)`) and assert the URL + parsed result
- [ ] Test the **rejection** path with `await expect(...).rejects.toThrow(...)`
- [ ] Use **fake timers** to prove `debounce` fires **once** after the delay
- [ ] Reset mocks between tests (`afterEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks())`)

**Acceptance:** no real network; async assertions are awaited; the debounce test is deterministic (no real waiting).

